segments.text: intramural situation.
And actually A&M had an excellent intramural program, which Penberthy, who I think was from Ohio State, really sort of was very innovative and so forth.
What were the most
important, the most respected activities in the intramurals?
What sports were most?
Well, actually probably intramural football was.
And then intramural basketball, but they also had everything.
They had wrestling, and they had boxing, and the outfits competed very vigorously for this intramural championship, which went on and wasn't awarded until the end of the year.
But for instance, when I was a freshman,
They had to have so many entrants in wrestling.
I'd never wrestled before in my life.
And so I went down and entered the wrestling deal and went up against some guy from West Texas.
He picked me up and we grappled around for a few minutes and finally he threw me out of the ring and broke my collarbone, which ended my wrestling career.
Was that your freshman?
My freshman year.
I think basketball season was over by then, so it didn't interfere with my basketball thing.
Where did you get treated for that injury?
At the hospital there.
I forget the doctor's name.
Marsh?
Dr. Marsh, wasn't it?
And Mom Claghorn, she was the principal nurse over there.
Describe her.
I recall Mom Claghorn, she was a,
a big woman who took charge of everything.
I mean, she, her word was, was indisputable, let's say.
Yeah.
Want a coffee, Reba, Phil?
We're talking about the hospital.
Right, right.
But, yeah, Dr. Marsh treated, treated everything, and, but Mom Claghorn was the
was the really, as I say, a big woman and her decision was not disputed by anybody.
Where did you and your buddies, if you had any unscheduled time during the day, where did you go if you had some off hours?
On the off hours, we'd go to the North Gate, as it was called.
What was up there?
Not very much.
Just cold drinks and
I think there was a movie theater up there too.
Campus theater.
But there were cold drinks and so forth.
And then let's see, the guys with, let's see,
large amounts of testosterone, managed to go into town and find some girls there.
A lot of them ended up marrying the gals they met in Bryan.
Now, during the day, what did y'all do at the Y?
At the Y, you could play ping-pong.
And you could also cash checks.
Mr. Cashin, as I recall, had the drugstore there.
And the drugstore was adjacent to the YMCA.
Describe Mr. Cashin as much as you recall about him.
I recall Mr. Cashin was a guy with horn-rimmed glasses who
actually looked very closely at the check he was trying to cash.
But he ran the drug store.
And he ran the Y.
Did you all have a nickname for him?
Not that I recall.
One of the nicknames I remember, they had the guy that used to hand out the uniforms and so forth in the
basketball park was a guy nicknamed Sarge for some reason.
Sarge had a nose that looked like W.C. Fields.
It had its ample supply of bourbon over the years.
Let's see, where did you get your mail?
Was it at the Y or at the Northgate?
I think we had mailboxes over in the administration building, but I'm not sure about that.
I'm hazy about that.
What kind of errands did a fish get to run for upperclassmen?
Anything they could think of.
Go to the North Gate, get them food, get magazines for them.
And actually, the way it was determined, they'd haul a fish.
An upper class would haul a fish, and everybody would run to that room, and the last one there had to run the air on it.
During those early months, where did you turn for advice about academics?
Who helped you if you couldn't figure out this homework problem?
Who did you turn to?
Well, actually, on homework, in my fish year, I became friends with Hank Gruy, who was a very smart guy.
And especially in math.
I was always very good in English.
But I would go to, Hank later became the, he has his own consulting firm, petroleum consulting firm.
And he was elected president of the Society of Petroleum Engineers.
And I remember one time getting stuck on a calculus problem.
I tried to work on about 830, and I went over to Hank's room, which he was in the engineers, and he had worked the problem and gone to bed.
But I turned to Hank on math as much as anything.
Now, your first semester, do you remember how you did academically?
I did well.
I think I was a distinguished student every year.
And you had gone to public high school?
Yes.
So you were well prepared.
I was well prepared.
Like I say, Barrett High School was a good school that I graduated from.
But actually in the country schools I went to, the teachers wanted to teach you something.
And I had a good foundation.
And I later went to MIT as a graduate student and was accepted there.
And I thought it was sort of interesting.
I think there were five of us from my class that went to MIT.
And we all did well.
I mean, we graduated without any problem.
In class, how did you and your buddies dress?
How did you behave?
What was normal?
decorum for class?
Well, there was no disputing the professors at all.
And, of course, you were dressed in the uniform and you paid attention and took notes and no disturbance in class.
Did you go to class every day?
Oh, yeah.
What about going to sleep in class?
Oh, the people that did that, quite a bit.
But actually, the classes were well controlled.
As you got into the subject that you were graduating in, those classes got much smaller, of course, and you had a lot of individual attention.
In freshman year, though, we had large classes like Tom Harrington teaching this chemical.
Were there some classes for freshmen or sophomores that everybody dreaded that were supposed to be real tough?
I can't answer your question exactly, but I remember there were some classes they thought
were real easy, you know.
What were they?
Well, physical education and actually, I guess, in the early stages, bull tax, as it was called, you know, was a military part of the deal.
And my mind just thinks about was the dog revelry already there?
Oh, yes.
I think Reveille appeared, I'm not sure it was my freshman year or had been there a year.
I think he'd been there a year.
But that little dog was a little black dog.
And the tradition was if that little dog came in your room and jumped up on your bed to sleep there, you had to go find another bed, you know.
Did that ever happen to you?
No, it happened to friends of mine, though.
And there was no, you know, get off the bed or anything, believe me.
I mean, people adhered to the, they wouldn't find another bed.
And as far as you all knew, where did Reveille, the original Reveille, come from?
Well, as I recall, the little dog was hit by a car, and two of the guys brought a,
brought her back to the vet's deal and the vets treated the little dog and the dog survived alright and just sort of wandered around the campus and also
apparently was attracted to the band and would bark when the band would play and march with the band to the football games.
Went to class sometimes?
Oh yeah, the little dog would go to class and come in classes.
Ever allowed in Sabeasa?
Oh yeah, the little dog had free rein anywhere.
That's what I've heard.
What about as a freshman, how soon was it before you and your buddies got involved in Good Bull, in pranks?
Well, of course, from the very first, they had a tradition of drowning out people.
And that happened when you were a freshman.
And actually, if there's somebody in your battery that you thought was brown-nosing, let's say, the guys would get together and say, let's round out so-and-so.
So, sure enough, at night, after the guy was asleep,
They'd run under two or three buckets of water and drown him out and run.
They never knew who had done that.
Did you ever do or did you ever participate in a drownout?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
Did you get caught?
No.
No.
Never did.
Now, the victim was usually in what class?
Sophomore or senior or what?
Well, it could be in either class.
I mean, the freshmen themselves round out guys that they thought were brown-nosing, let's say.
So it might even be another fish.
Oh, yeah, another fish.
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.
Describe, if you can, your going to your first Aggie football game.
Describe that whole weekend and all that went on.
Well, I don't recall the first weekend, but I do recall the TCU game.
Because A&M hadn't beaten TCU in 10 or 12 years, something like that.
And so they had a rally on the YMCA steps.
And I remember he introduced the football team.
Joe Rout got up, made a speech, and so forth.
But beating TCU at that time was a big deal.
I'm trying to think.
The first football game, of course, we had the tradition was standing up and so forth.
Did you all have a Yale practice the night before?
Oh, yeah.
Where?
Yeah, we had a Yale practice the night before.
Do you remember where Yale practices were then?
I don't remember.
I don't remember where they were.
Then Saturday morning you went to class.
Yes, I recall Saturday morning after class we were off Saturday afternoon.
So you were free to do things, catch up on your... Did you all have, for going to the game on Saturday afternoon, did you all march in to the stadium?
I'm quite sure we did.
I'm sort of hazy on that, but I'm quite sure we marched in.
Yeah, we marched everywhere.
And you stood up at the game.
Oh, yeah, you stood up at the game.
All right, then did y'all win that TCU game that year?
I don't recall, except I just recall the buildup beforehand.
When you did win the game, did you all capture the L-eaters?
Yeah, as I recall, we did.
We threw them in the fish pond.
Then on a Saturday night, after a game or anything else, where did you and your buddies go your first year or two on a Saturday night?
On a Saturday night,
A lot of guys went to a place called Hard Liquor's.
They had Hard Liquor's and drank beer.
I never was a
much of a beer drinker, so I think I'd go to a movie or something like that.
But a good many of these guys went to.
Now during your first year, you said your father had died when you were a youngster.
Your mother's still living.
Right, right.
Who did you write to and who did you get mail from?
My mother, principally, and a couple of girlfriends from Shreveport, and some that I met on court trips.
Describe a court trip.
A court trip, you'd come to Dallas, let's say, and you'd check into a hotel usually about
as many as could get in a room, you know.
Only a couple of guys would sign for it, but really about four or five guys stayed there at the office or somewhere.
You'd march up Main Street and have Yale practice in front of the hotel, as I recall.
And then they were, and you usually
In Dallas, you usually met a bunch of girls that came down from CIA.
Anyway, usually after a court trip, you had a correspondence going with somebody from Denton.
How did you make contact?
Did you write to them first?
No, you sort of met them in the lobby of the office, let's say.
How did you pick the one that interested you?
Well, just the, I'd say just the normal chemistry between somebody, you know, that somebody that conversation and so forth was, and maybe he'd take them to dinner, whatever, and
Did Aggies behave pretty well around young ladies in those days?
Oh, yes.
Yes, I think they did.
I mean, there was a different code at that time than now.
I mean, there was a respect for women at that time.
Did any of your student friends have a car?
Only a few.
Only a few had cars.
I remember one of them was the Mitchells from Houston.
And Johnny Mitchell and George, they had convertibles, as a matter of fact, which was a big deal at that time.
What kind of convertible?
Do you remember?
I don't remember.
They were just convertibles.
Wow.
Big men on the campus were there.
Where were the student parking places then?
I'm not sure, but I remember there were places you couldn't park.
I remember Bobby Early, who I played on the tennis team with, he had an A-model Ford, and he parked it in a no-parking place.
And anyway, they confiscated the car and took part of the thing off so he couldn't start the car.
And he had to go down and see the commandant before he could get the car back, and he had to pay a fine.
Bobby did that.
Back to football.
core trips went to Fort Worth and Dallas and Houston and Austin.
Of all of your years, do you have any special memories of core trips, plus or minus?
Yeah, I think the core trip I remember mostly is a TCU core trip because on that core trip
I met a gal named Frances Buster whose father was a professor at TCU, and she later married Davey O'Brien, as a matter of fact.
But she was really a cute little thing, and we corresponded for maybe six or seven months, something like that.
But that's why I remember that course.
Do you remember how you met her?
I think I met in the lobby of the hotel, you know, one of the hotels there.
And anything, do you remember any sad things on a court trip ever?
Yeah, I remember the sad thing, I remember Bobby Early, he had signed up for
was a room I think was in Dallas.
And this was, I think, his junior year.
And anyway, there were a whole bunch of, there was some,
Bobby was in A Troop Cavalry, and I remember, and they were, but he was signed up for the room, but he actually, actually didn't ever go to the room.
He went, he had some other friends, and he stayed with them, ran into them, or some other thing, and these other people really tore up the room.
I mean, they, so Bobby got nailed for it,
And actually it cost him his commission.
And he was never there.
Do you remember your first silver taps?
I don't remember the first one.
I remember I was so impressed the first time I heard it.
Describe why.
I think I understand, but make believe I didn't understand why a silver taps was special.
Well, they blew silver towels when of course anybody died, any cadet died, and I remember
It was at night and a cold clear night in the fall and the notes of that bugle just seemed to be the only thing there that really stirred up your emotions to think that
that one of your fellow cadets was remembered this way.
And was Silver Taps always taken seriously?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
Nobody ever broke the rules?
Oh, no.
Not that I know of.
Make believe I'd never been.
Where was it held, and what happened?

Well, as I recall, it was just the bugler himself who was there, and the bugle stand was in front of the administration building then, and a big megaphone, you know, and you could hear it all over the campus.
You were in your room when they blew it.
And then you came over, ceremony, and then went back to your room?
No, you just stayed in there.
I mean, there was no ceremony at all.
Oh, really?
No, there was no ceremony.
Oh, you all didn't gather?
No, no, no.
There was no ceremony.
You were just in your room when the silver caps was blown.
Did you turn out the lights then after it was over?
As I recall, it was done at...
I really am hazy on that, exactly what happened, but I remember you were in your room when they blew it, but you knew who the cadet was that was being honored.
You knew that.
And I'm not sure how you knew that, but you knew that.
Your freshman year, you didn't go home, I presume, until Thanksgiving?
We went to, I think we went over, the first time we went home actually was, A&M was playing Centenary over in Shreveport.
So, Bobby Earley had this old A Model Ford.
that he had retrieved from the commandant.
So we drove over for the game, and that old car, the problem was how much oil it used.
You had to carry several quarts of oil all the time.
And cold?
Man, it was cold.
But anyway, we went to Shreveport for the game, and so that was sometime in the fall.
Did you entertain your buddies in Shreveport?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
What did you do for them on Saturday night?
Do you remember?
On Saturday night, I think I took them to the Washington Urey Hotel, as a matter of fact.
I took Bobby, anyway.
Bobby was a very close friend.
All right.
Then did you go back Thanksgiving?
Back home, I reckon?
I don't think I went back home until Christmas, as a matter of fact.
Did you always take the train back and forth?
Yeah, you took the train, unless somebody was driving back.
But it was a pretty long trip then, you know, so I took the train.
And you wore your uniform going and coming.
Right, right.
What did you feel like on the train with you, wearing that Aggie uniform?
Well, you usually drew some attention, you know, good or bad.
Can you give some examples of the good or the bad?
Well, I'd say that, you know, people that knew a little about A&M would come up and say, I had a cousin that went here or so and so, you know, and I got to go to the men's room.
Did anybody ever tease you when you were wearing your Aggie uniform on the train or the bus?
I'm sure they did.
I can't remember any particular incidents, but I'm sure that must have happened.
But I can't remember any particular answer.
All right, summarize that.
When you finished that freshman year, how did you feel about being an Aggie?
Well, at the end of the freshman year, I felt good.
I felt, one, I had survived a really tough year, and two, that I would now be a sophomore and would have the privileges I didn't have before.
And I was pleased with the
my academics at that time and I thought I was progressing well toward a degree and I loved the school after after that first year and and people
who were in the freshman class with me that enrolled at the very first, they either liked the school or they didn't, almost from the very first.
And one of the things that I recognized at A&M at that time was that it wasn't, they judged a person about not who he was, but what he was.
I mean, there's a difference in who and what.
For instance, one of my classmates was Bert Hull.
His father had built the tap line pipeline from Texas up to New York.
He was the president of Texaco Pipeline Company.
And he built the pipeline in Saudi Arabia.
And so Burt was, his father was quite wealthy.
But to illustrate what I'm saying, he used to say, well, don't make old Burt mad.
They called him Balbo.
Don't make Balbo mad.
his old man might run a pipeline right through the mess hall.
So somebody with, let's say, with a certain amount of wealth really had to overcome that to a certain extent.
About how many started out in your outfit, do you remember, as a freshman?
I don't remember, except that I would say at the end of the year, I would just estimate that two-thirds remained after the first year.
Of those who did not
come back, about how many flunked out and how many couldn't afford to come, didn't have the money, or how many just didn't like A&M and went somewhere else?
I'd say about a third, a third, and a third.
One of my roommates was a fellow named Hudson Vanloon.
Hudson was from Shreveport.
I'd known him in high school.
Hudson loved A&M, but he flunked out.
He flunked out every semester.

and I used to be somewhat jealous of Hudson because when he and I would be walking down the sidewalk and we occasionally would pass Dean Brooks who was Hudson was in his in his school Dean Brooks knew Hudson quite well he'd say Hudson how are you and he didn't know who I was you know and Hudson had to go see Dean Brooks about every two months but he Hudson flunked out to and and he'd be uh
He flunked out three times, I think, but he loved A&M.
The academics were tough and the life was tough.
I think one thing in retrospect I observed was that when you're together in a situation or situations where the times are tough, no matter what they are,
You form a friendship there that is a bonding that you'll never forget.
The same thing happened in the Army with people that you're under stress with and you make friends with.
Those type of friendships are lasting.
Did you feel those bonds already
in beginning to be in place in your freshman year?
Oh yes, freshman year.
I knew that I had friends there that I could call on in times of trouble.
Did you ever think about dropping out?
No, no.
I never thought about dropping out.
My thought was I always wanted to take graduate studies at MIT because of the reputation.
And so my whole emphasis was on making grades good enough so that I'd be accepted in graduate school at MIT.
During that freshman year, do you have any idea how much it cost?
I don't know.
My mother,
Fortunately, when my father died, he had just taken out an insurance policy of $50,000.
And he died about three months later, a ruptured appendix.
But he left my mother with this $50,000 plus a cotton plantation of about 2,000 acres.
And my mother, being a schoolteacher, really emphasized education.
She took care of all the bills.
Did you have spending money?
Yes.
Oh, yes.
I had a certain amount.
I had an allowance.
What did you spend that allowance on?
Usually on Coca-Cola and sandwiches and magazines and nothing very exciting.
But my mother sent me allowance every month.
Now, you went to the movie.
Right.
Gynon Hall.
